"""
MKT Context Commentary — Job chapters 5–7
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-job-5-7.py
Verses: ch5×27 + ch6×30 + ch7×21 = 78

Key notes:
- ch5: Eliphaz concludes his first speech; v7 'sons of Resheph' preserves a Canaanite
  plague-deity reference; v13 is quoted by Paul in 1 Cor 3:19; v17's beatitude formula
  is the OT antecedent of Heb 12:5-6; vv23-26 echo covenant-blessing formulas.
- ch6: Job's first reply; the wadi-metaphor (vv15-20) references actual ANE caravan
  routes — Tema (Tayma, NW Arabia) and Sheba (S Arabia). v14's ḥeseḏ as friendship
  obligation is distinctive; vv22-24 deploy the legal-deposition form.
- ch7: Job's soliloquy on human existence; v1 ṣāḇāʾ = forced service (Isa 40:2);
  v12 invokes the Yam/sea-monster motif from Canaanite creation mythology; v17's
  'what is man' is a deliberate counter-inversion of Ps 8:4.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOB57 = {
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 5 continues Eliphaz's first speech begun in ch4. Eliphaz is the eldest and most senior of the three friends (his later speech in ch15 calls him the first to speak). The question 'to which of the holy ones will you appeal?' invokes the concept of the <em>divine council</em> — the assembly of heavenly beings who serve YHWH (1 Kgs 22:19-22; Ps 82; 89:5-7; Isa 6:1-8). In Job's context the question is rhetorical: no member of the divine court will intercede for Job because (Eliphaz assumes) Job is guilty. The 'holy ones' (qĕḏōšîm) in the council appear in Zech 14:5; Dan 8:13; and the Qumran community called itself the 'congregation of the holy ones.'</p>",
    "2": "<p>Eliphaz cites a wisdom maxim: anger (kāʿas, vexation) kills the fool and jealousy (qinʾāh, zeal/envy) destroys the credulous. This connects to the wisdom tradition's warnings about uncontrolled passion as self-destructive: Prov 12:16 ('a fool shows his annoyance at once'); Prov 14:17,29; 27:3-4 on the destructive power of anger and envy. The verse implies Job's complaints are self-destructive expressions of a fool's anger — a pointed personal accusation wrapped in the form of a general proverb.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Eliphaz appeals to his personal observation as epistemological authority — 'I have seen' (rāʾîṯî) — a standard wisdom source alongside tradition (v27: 'we have examined') and dream-vision (4:12-17). The retributive framework is confirmed by the sudden cursing (ʾārar) of the fool's household; the suddenness (pitʾōm) is characteristic of the wisdom tradition's expectation of divine justice (Prov 6:15; 29:1). The curse on offspring for the father's sin reflects the Deuteronomic understanding of multigenerational consequences (Exod 20:5; Deut 5:9).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The crushing of the fool's children 'at the city gate' (šaʿar) places the justice scenario in the legal-commercial hub of the ancient city. The city gate was where legal cases were heard (Ruth 4:1-11; Amos 5:12,15; Prov 31:23), disputes adjudicated, and commerce conducted. To be crushed at the gate without a rescuer (mōšîaʿ) is to lack all the protective networks that city-gate society provided — legal advocates, family connections, or divine intervention.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The image of the hungry eating up the fool's harvest 'from among the thorns' (min-qōṣ) reflects the agricultural vulnerability of the ancient Near East: inadequate fencing, drought, and raider attacks could devastate a harvest. The verse may preserve a proverb about the fragility of ill-gotten or unprotected gains. The motif of others consuming what the guilty planted is a standard covenant-curse formula (Deut 28:30,33: 'you will plant a vineyard but not enjoy it'; Lev 26:16).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Verse 6-7 form a two-part unit: v6 states the negative (trouble does not arise spontaneously from nature), v7 states the positive counterpart. The rhetorical structure mirrors ANE wisdom-literature forms where negation precedes affirmation to make the affirmation stronger. The verse denies that suffering is a natural accident — instead it is purposefully connected to human behavior, setting up Eliphaz's disciplinary theology in v17.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The phrase <span class='term'>'sons of Resheph fly upward'</span> (bĕnê-rešep̄ yagbîhû ʿûp̄) preserves a reference to <em>Resheph</em>, the Canaanite god of plague, pestilence, and burning fever (attested in Ugaritic texts as rsp and in Egyptian inscriptions where Resheph is depicted as an archer). The 'sons of Resheph' are sparks or arrows — the fiery symptoms of plague. The MKT renders it as 'sparks fly upward' following the common English interpretation, but the mythological background suggests that trouble in human life has the inevitability of a deity's arrows being released. The image is demythologized compared to its Canaanite origin but retains the ANE conception of suffering as divinely launched projectiles (see also 6:4 where Job uses 'arrows of Shaddai').</p>",
    "8": "<p>Eliphaz's advice is framed in first-person hypothetical: 'as for me, I would seek God' (ʾănî ʾeḏrōš ʾel-ʾēl). The seeking-God vocabulary is central to Israel's worship tradition (Ps 14:2; 27:8; Isa 55:6; Amos 5:4-6 'seek me and live'; the repeated 'seek YHWH/God' formula in the prophets and Psalms). Eliphaz is recommending exactly what the wisdom tradition demands — but in a context where Job is already seeking and not finding, the advice becomes inadvertently ironic.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The praise of God as doing 'great and unsearchable things' (gĕḏōlôṯ wĕʾên ḥēqer) echoes a standard doxological formula found in the Psalms (77:14; 86:10; 136:4) and Isaiah (40:28 'his understanding is unsearchable'). The participial style of vv9-16 — listing God's mighty acts — is a hymnic form characteristic of the Psalms (e.g., Ps 103:3-10; 104; 107) and wisdom poetry; the friends frequently employ the hymn-form as part of their arguments, using praise of divine power as implicit leverage against Job's complaint.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Rain as divine blessing is a constant OT theological claim: Deut 11:11-14 makes rain in its season the specific covenant-blessing contingent on obedience; Ps 65:9-13 celebrates God watering the earth; Isa 55:10 uses rain as a metaphor for the word of God accomplishing its purpose. In the ANE context of semi-arid Palestine and Mesopotamia, where rain determined survival, its attribution to YHWH rather than Baal (the storm/rain deity; 1 Kgs 18) was a theological claim about where true power resided.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The lifting-of-the-lowly and raising-of-mourners formula appears throughout Israel's worship tradition as a foundational attribute of YHWH's justice: 1 Sam 2:7-8 (Hannah's Song: 'he raises the poor from the dust'); Ps 113:7-9; Luke 1:52 (Magnificat). The pairing of 'low ones' (šĕp̄ālîm) with those in mourning (qĕḏārîm, 'darkened/in mourning-dress') reflects the double vulnerability of poverty and grief that divine justice specifically addresses.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The frustration of the cunning's schemes is a wisdom-tradition theme developed in Prov 3:7 ('do not be wise in your own eyes'); 11:2 ('pride comes, then disgrace'); and 26:27 ('whoever digs a pit will fall in it'). In the prophets, the cunning who devise evil against the helpless are specifically targeted by divine reversal (Isa 29:14; Mic 2:1-3). The wisdom tradition consistently argues that elaborate human scheming fails because it does not account for divine oversight.</p>",
    "13": "<p>This verse is directly quoted by Paul in 1 Corinthians 3:19 ('he catches the wise in their craftiness' — the only direct NT quotation from the book of Job). Paul deploys it in his argument that worldly wisdom is foolishness before God and that the Corinthians should not boast in human leaders. The NT application shifts the context: Eliphaz uses it as a warning to Job, but Paul uses it to undercut the very kind of confident wisdom-claiming that Eliphaz represents. Eliphaz quotes wisdom to trap Job; Paul quotes Job to unmask the trap of wisdom-confidence itself.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The reversal of light and darkness — 'they encounter darkness in broad daylight' — is a standard prophetic sign of divine judgment against the corrupt powerful (Amos 5:18-20: the Day of YHWH as darkness, not light; Isa 8:22; 59:9-10: 'we grope like the blind along the wall... we stumble at noon as in the twilight'). The midday darkness as punishment is also the plague-of-darkness motif from Exod 10:21-23, where Egypt experiences darkness while Israel has light — the same reversal Eliphaz describes.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The salvation of the poor from the 'cutting words' (<span class='term'>ḥereb</span>, literally 'sword') of enemies reflects the ancient understanding that verbal violence — false accusation, slander, and incitement — was a weapon comparable to physical harm. The Psalms repeatedly describe the tongue as a sword (57:4; 64:3; Prov 12:18); in the legal context, false testimony could literally destroy a person's life and livelihood. 'The grip of the powerful' (min-yāḏ ḥāzāq) — the powerful hand as instrument of oppression is a standard OT justice-concern (Ps 35:10; 140:4).</p>",
    "16": "<p>'The poor find hope' (wattihî lĕʾeḇyôn tiqwāh) — tiqwāh (hope) as the specific possession of those the world has written off is a major prophetic theme: Isa 40:31 ('those who hope in YHWH will renew their strength'); Jer 29:11 ('plans for a future and a hope'); Lam 3:24 ('YHWH is my portion; therefore I will hope in him'). The verse ends 'injustice is silenced' (ʿawlāh qāp̄ĕṣāh pîhā = injustice shuts its mouth) — the personification of injustice as a speaking mouth that gets silenced when God acts is a vivid legal metaphor.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Blessed is the person whom God reproves' — this <em>beatitude formula</em> (ʾašrê hāgāḇer ʾăšer yôḵiḥennû ʾĕlôah) is the OT antecedent to Hebrews 12:5-6, which quotes Proverbs 3:11-12 ('do not despise the LORD's discipline') in the context of suffering-as-training. The makarism/beatitude form (ʾašrê = blessed is the one who...) is characteristic of Psalm openings (Ps 1:1; 32:1-2; 119:1-2) and the Sermon on the Mount (Matt 5:3-12). Eliphaz is offering Job a theological framework for his suffering — discipline leads to restoration — that is genuinely true as a general principle but falsely applied to Job's specific situation.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The 'wound and bandage' theology of v18 parallels Hosea 6:1 ('he has torn us but will heal us; he has struck us down and will bind up our wounds') and Isaiah 30:26 ('when YHWH binds up the bruises of his people'). The medical imagery of divine wounding-then-healing is part of the Deuteronomic and prophetic understanding of suffering as remedial: the same God who strikes also heals. Deut 32:39 makes the claim most starkly: 'I kill and I make alive; I have wounded and I will heal.' The NT fulfillment is the crucified-and-risen Christ as the wounded healer.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The 'six troubles... seven' formula is a <em>graded numerical saying</em> characteristic of Semitic wisdom literature (cf. Prov 6:16 'six things the LORD hates, seven that are detestable'; Amos 1:3,6,9 'for three transgressions... and for four'). The formula expresses totality and completeness — no matter how many troubles come (up to the symbolic limit of seven), God will deliver. The numerical formula appears in Ugaritic literature as well, confirming its ANE wisdom-genre roots. The promise of complete deliverance through all combinations of trouble is meant to reassure Job, though it ironically describes exactly the comprehensive suffering Job has already experienced.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Redemption from famine and war are the two paradigmatic threats to ancient Israelite life: famine controlled by rain and harvest (connected to Deut 11 obedience-rain theology), and war as the primary external threat. The promise to redeem from 'the lethal edge of the sword' (mîḏê ḥāreḇ) uses the covenant-protection vocabulary of Ps 144:10 and the Deuteronomic blessing-curses, where military defeat is a specific covenant curse (Deut 28:25-26) and military victory a covenant blessing.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The 'lash of the tongue' (šôṭ lāšôn) — the tongue as a whip is a powerful wisdom metaphor for destructive speech; the same metaphor appears in Prov 18:21 ('death and life are in the power of the tongue'); Ps 31:20 ('from the strife of tongues'); and the NT: James 3:5-8 (the tongue as a fire and unruly evil). The promise to be sheltered from verbal attack is particularly poignant given that Job's suffering has included the verbal attacks of his three friends and the mockery of v9.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'You will laugh at destruction and famine' — śāḥaq (to laugh) directed at the threats of destruction (šôḏ) and famine (kāp̄ān) is the confidence of the protected covenant member. The same laughter-at-enemies motif appears in Ps 2:4 (God laughing at the nations), Ps 37:13 (YHWH laughing at the wicked), and the wisdom theme that the righteous will outlive all threats (Prov 1:26). 'Wild animals of the land' (ḥayyôṯ hāʾāreṣ) — in the ancient Near East, predatory animals were a genuine threat to human habitation; they feature in Deut 28:26 as a covenant curse.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'A covenant with the stones of the field' — the covenant (bĕrît) with inanimate natural forces is an unusual formulation that reflects the ANE understanding of the natural world as covenantally ordered. Hosea 2:18 (Israel's restoration) describes a covenant with animals and weapons: 'I will make a covenant for them with the wild animals, the birds, and the creatures that move along the ground.' The broader concept is of a creation covenant in which the righteous live in harmony with the natural order — the Edenic condition of Gen 1-2 restored. Wild animals at peace with the human reflects the 'peaceable kingdom' motif of Isa 11:6-9.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The secure home (šālôm) and full flocks are the specific components of ANE prosperity: a household (ʾōhel/nāweh) that does not experience loss, and livestock that reproduce without loss (peqûddāh = musters/counts of the flock). In the ancient pastoral economy, flock numbers were the primary indicator of wealth. The promise repeats the content of Job's pre-disaster condition as described in 1:3: 'seven thousand sheep, three thousand camels...' — Eliphaz is essentially promising Job his ch1 life back if he submits.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Numerous offspring like the grass of the earth (keʿēśeḇ hāʾāreṣ) echoes the Abrahamic covenant-promise: Gen 22:17 ('I will make your offspring as numerous as the stars of the sky and the sand on the seashore'); Gen 28:14 ('your offspring will be like the dust of the earth'). The grass-of-earth simile specifically appears in Ps 72:16 for the flourishing of the righteous king's subjects. The patriarchal promise of numerous descendants as the sign of divine blessing is here presented as the reward awaiting Job's repentance.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Come to your grave in ripe old age, like a sheaf of grain harvested in its season' — the death-in-old-age-in-its-proper-time is a standard covenant-blessing formula. Gen 15:15 promises Abram: 'you shall go to your fathers in peace; you shall be buried in a good old age.' The harvest-sheaf metaphor for a timely, dignified death (bĕkaleah qāmeh) emphasizes the season-appropriate nature of the righteous death: not premature, not violent, not protracted, but complete and gathered at the proper moment. The agricultural metaphor integrates human life and death into the rhythms of creation's ordered bounty.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Eliphaz closes his speech with the claim of collective empirical validation: 'we have examined this carefully; it is true' (hinnēh-zōʾṯ ḥăqarnûhāh kēn-hîʾ). The verb ḥāqar (to search out/investigate) is the language of wisdom research (8:8; Eccl 1:13; Prov 25:2). 'Hear it and know it for yourself' (šĕmāʿennāh wĕʾattāh ḏāʿ-lāḵ) — the imperatives of hearing and knowing frame his conclusion as a universally accessible truth. The corporate 'we' validates the three-friends' unanimity. Job's response will reject both the content and the epistemological confidence of this claim.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 6 opens Job's first formal reply to Eliphaz. The narrative formula 'then Job replied' (wayyaʿan ʾîyôḇ wayyōʾmer) marks each new speech; the book's dialogue structure alternates between a friend's speech and Job's reply in three complete cycles (chs. 4-14, 15-21, 22-31) before Elihu (32-37) and God (38-41). The order Eliphaz-Job-Bildad-Job-Zophar-Job is maintained in cycles 1 and 2; in cycle 3 only Eliphaz and Bildad speak before Job's great oath of clearance (ch31) closes his case.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Job opens with a wish that his grief could be weighed on scales (mōʾzĕnayim), directly responding to Eliphaz's implied measurement of Job's sin as the cause of his suffering. The scales/balance metaphor is a standard wisdom motif for divine justice (Prov 16:11; 11:1; 20:23), and Job inverts it: not his sin but his <em>grief</em> should be weighed. The term 'calamity' (hawwāṯî, from hawwāh = ruin/disaster) appears frequently in Job and the Psalms for catastrophic suffering; its weight is literally immeasurable ('heavier than the sand of the sea,' v3).</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Heavier than the sand of the sea' (kāḇēḏ mikḥôl yammîm) — the sand-of-the-sea is the standard OT hyperbole for incalculability (Gen 22:17; 32:12; Hos 1:10; Rev 20:8). Job is claiming that his suffering exceeds the capacity of any measurement system — the friends' retributive calculus cannot compute it. The acknowledgment that his 'words have been rash' (lāḵēn ḏĕḇāray lāʿû) is a concession: Job knows his language in ch3 was extreme, but he attributes it to the weight of his suffering rather than impiety.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'The Almighty's arrows are lodged in me' — the divine-archer imagery draws on both the wisdom tradition and ANE mythology. Ps 38:2 uses identical imagery: 'your arrows have pierced me'; Ps 7:13 describes God preparing his weapons against the wicked. The word translated 'venom' (ḥămaṯām = their poison) recalls the poisoned arrows of ancient warfare; the arrows are not merely painful but venomous — they contaminate the wound with additional suffering. 'Terrors of God' (bîʿûṯê ʾĕlôah) — bîʿāh = terror, overwhelm; God's own terrors are personified as an army arrayed against Job, which the military metaphor of 'arrayed against me' (yaʿarĕḵûnî) makes explicit.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Job employs animal proverbs to defend the proportionality of his complaints: a wild donkey (pere', the symbol of free, undomesticated nature; Gen 16:12 applies this word to Ishmael) doesn't bray over fresh grass, and an ox doesn't bellow over its fodder. The ANE proverbial tradition used animal behavior as an argument from nature to establish norms of proportionate response. Job's argument: my complaints are not gratuitous — they are proportionate to genuine deprivation, just as animal cries are proportionate to genuine need.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The food proverbs continue: tasteless food without salt, the white of an egg with no flavor. Salt (melaḥ) was the indispensable condiment and food preservative of the ancient world, so scarce in inland areas that it functioned as currency and gave its name to several words (including 'salary' in Latin). 'The white of an egg' (rîr ḥallāmûṯ) is a hapax; translations vary widely. The point is that Job's suffering has made even normal food nauseating — his appetite has been corrupted by the substance of his pain, just as tasteless food is rejected by a healthy appetite.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The verse expresses complete sensory revulsion: 'my appetite refuses to touch such things' — the conventional food the friends offer (their theological comfort) is as unpalatable as loathsome food (kĕḏewî laḥmî = like the illness/sorrow of my food). The passage from v5 to v7 moves from the reasonableness of complaint to the total corruption of appetite — Job cannot even receive normal comfort, not because he refuses it but because his suffering has made it impossible to ingest.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The optative wish (mî-yittēn = 'O that!') is one of Job's characteristic rhetorical forms: he uses it to express desires that he knows are beyond normal reach but that define what he genuinely needs. Here his request is not healing but death — specifically, to be 'cut off' (yiḇṣāʿēnî = he cuts me off; bāṣaʿ = to cut off, used for breaking threads). The desire for death as relief from unbearable suffering is a recurring theme in the OT: Moses (Num 11:15), Elijah (1 Kgs 19:4), Jonah (4:3,8), Jeremiah (20:14-18). Job joins this company of those whose suffering reached the limit of endurance.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The request that God 'crush me, let loose his hand and cut me off' — the three verbs (crush = yĕdakkĕʾēnî, let loose = yatter, cut off = yiḇṣāʿēnî) describe a comprehensive divine act of termination. The theological significance is that Job is asking God to be the agent of his death, not anyone else. This is not suicidal despair but theodicy: if God is the one who has brought this suffering, let God also be the one who ends it. The request for divine termination rather than human comfort frames death as the only adequate divine response to divinely inflicted suffering.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'I have not concealed the words of the Holy One' (lōʾ kihhadtî ʾimrê qāḏôš) — Job's ground of consolation even in death would be his consistent integrity in not suppressing or denying what God's word/will demanded of him. kāḥaḏ (to hide/deny by concealment) appears in Josh 7:19 for Achan's hiding of sin; Job uses its negative: he has not hidden his acknowledgment of God's word. The 'Holy One' (qāḏôš) is the title used by Isaiah for YHWH (Isa 1:4; 5:19 'the Holy One of Israel'), giving Job's confession of faithfulness a specifically monotheistic grounding.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The two questions — 'what is my strength, that I should hold on?' (mah-kōḥî kî ʾăyaḥēl) and 'what do I have to look forward to, that I should endure?' (mah-qiṣṣî kî ʾaʾărîḵ nap̄šî) — establish the limits of human endurance. Strength (kōaḥ) and future-orientation (qēṣ = end/goal) are the two foundations of perseverance; without either, endurance loses its ground. This is not complaint but honest diagnosis: what resources are available to keep going? The verse anticipates the NT's reframing of endurance as possible only with external strengthening (2 Cor 12:9; Phil 4:13; Heb 12:1-3).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The stone/bronze simile for impossible endurance: stone (ʾāḇen) is the OT symbol for hardness and permanence (Job 38:30; Ezek 11:19 where God promises to replace the 'stone heart' with a 'heart of flesh'); bronze (nĕḥûšāh) is hard, unyielding metal. Job's rhetorical question implies that endurance requires inhuman material composition — he is not stone or bronze, he is flesh, and flesh has limits. The frailty-of-flesh theme runs through Job (4:19; 10:4-9; 14:1-2) and connects to the NT's consistent acknowledgment that human weakness requires divine strength (2 Cor 4:7-9; Heb 4:15).</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Is there no help left in me? Has all sound judgment been driven away from me?' — the verse registers the total depletion of internal resources: ʾên-ʿezrāṯî ḇî (no help is in me), tûšiyyāh (sound wisdom/effective capability, the distinctive Joban term; see 12:16; 26:3) niddĕḥāh mimmenî (driven from me, as if scattered by a storm). Total internal depletion is the condition under which Job makes his complaint — not from abundance of options but from their complete exhaustion.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'The despairing person deserves steadfast love from a friend' (lammās mērēʿēhû ḥāseḏ) — this verse is theologically significant because it applies <span class='term'>ḥeseḏ</span> (covenant-loyalty/steadfast love, the term for YHWH's faithful relationship with Israel: Exod 34:6-7; Ps 136) to the horizontal relationship between human friends. ḥeseḏ as a social obligation between humans appears in Ruth 3:10 (Ruth's ḥeseḏ toward Naomi); Gen 21:23 (covenantal ḥeseḏ between humans); Prov 19:22. 'To withhold it is to forsake the fear of the Almighty' — the friends' failure of ḥeseḏ toward Job is simultaneously a failure of their theology: proper fear of God should produce ḥeseḏ toward his image-bearer in distress.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'My brothers are as treacherous as a seasonal brook' — the wadi metaphor begins. The wadis of the Negev and Sinai are intermittent streams that flow only during winter rains and completely dry up in summer. As a metaphor for unreliable friends, the wadi is apt: it appears when least needed (in the cold season when water is not scarce) and disappears when most needed (in the heat and drought). The treachery (ḇāgad = to act treacherously, the word for covenant-betrayal in Prov 2:22; Mal 2:14-16) of the friends is like the wadi's disappearance: predictable given the conditions, but devastating to those who counted on the water.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The technical description of the wadi's winter flow: darkened by melting ice (qādēr min-qaraḥ = dark from ice), swollen where snow lies hidden (yitʿallēm-ʿālaw šāleg = snow hidden/covered upon it). The semi-arid Sinai and Negev regions do receive occasional winter snow; the melting contributes to the winter wadi-flow that creates the paradox: the stream is fullest in the season when water is least needed for survival.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The disappearance in summer: 'when the heat comes they vanish' (ḇĕʿēṯ zārĕbû niṣmāṯû = in the time they are scorched, they are cut off). niṣmāṯû (from ṣāmat = to silence/cut off; also used in Ps 94:23 for God cutting off the wicked). The summer heat that makes water most critical is precisely when the wadi 'dries up from its channel' (yidʿăkû mimqômām). The seasonal pattern of the unreliable wadi mirrors the friends' behavior: present when Job was prosperous (ch29), absent now in his extremity.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'The courses they ran turn aside; they rise into wasteland and vanish' (yilpĕṯû ʾorḥôṯ darqām yĕhalikû ḇatōhû wayyōʾḇēḏû). The word tōhû (wasteland/formlessness, the primordial void of Gen 1:2) is applied to the empty space into which the wadi's waters disappear — literally evaporating into nothingness. The use of the creation-language word tōhû for the friends' destination gives their disappearance cosmic resonance: the unreliable friends return to the formless void that preceded creation.</p>",
    "19": "<p><span class='term'>Tema</span> and <span class='term'>Sheba</span> are historically identifiable Arabian locations. Tema (modern Tayma) is an oasis city in northwest Arabia (Isa 21:14; Jer 25:23; Ezra 2:53) that controlled major caravan routes through the northern Arabian desert; it was significant enough for Nabonidus (Babylonian king) to relocate there for a decade (556-539 BCE). Sheba (in southern Arabia, modern Yemen) was the source of gold, spices, and incense that traveled north through Arabia on the incense route (1 Kgs 10:1-13, the Queen of Sheba; Isa 60:6; Ps 72:10). The caravans of these two major trade centers looking for water makes the wadi metaphor geographically precise: actual trading parties died when expected water sources failed.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'They are put to shame because they trusted them' (ḇōšû kî-ḇāṭāḥ = they are ashamed because they trusted) — bāṭaḥ (to trust/rely on) is the standard vocabulary for faith/trust (Ps 22:4-5; Prov 3:5; Isa 31:1; Jer 17:5-8); its application to the caravan's misplaced trust in the wadi explicitly parallels the problem of trusting unreliable comfort. 'They come and find themselves disappointed' — the travelers' experience of arriving at a dry wadi to find nothing is the exact experience of Job encountering his friends: he came hoping for water and found emptiness.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'You have become just like them' — Job makes the application of the wadi metaphor explicit. The shift to second person (lî hĕyîṯem lōʾ = you have become nothing to me) is a direct accusation. 'You see my disaster and shrink back in fear' — the friends' withdrawal is not merely unhelpful but is an active display: they are afraid (tîrāʾû = you are frightened) at the sight of Job's suffering. The fear-response to suffering in one's friend is a theme in the Psalms (38:11; 88:8,18: 'my companions avoid me because of my wounds').</p>",
    "22": "<p>Job denies making any financial requests of the friends: he has not asked for a 'gift' (šōḥaḏ = a bribe or present; the word has both neutral and pejorative senses — a gift to influence, cf. Prov 17:8,23; 18:16) from their wealth. The question is rhetorical: of course he hasn't. The verse establishes that Job's needs are not material but relational and theological — he wants truth (v25-26), not money. The absence of financial demands makes the friends' silence and inadequate response all the more inexcusable.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The two further negatives — 'save me from my enemy's hand' (pĕlṭûnî = rescue me), 'rescue me from the grip of the ruthless' (ûmiyyad ʿārîṣîm tippĕḏûnî = ransom me from the hand of the violent) — establish that Job has asked for none of the normal things one asks friends for: money, legal defense, protection from enemies. His need is categorically different from the standard social obligations of friendship, yet the friends still fail him at the most basic level.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Teach me and I will be quiet' (hôrûnî wăʾănî ʾaḥărîš) — Job's offer is a genuine invitation: if the friends can actually demonstrate his sin, he will accept their conclusion in silence. 'Show me where I have gone wrong' (ûmah šāgîṯî hăḇînû lî = and where I have erred, make me understand). The vocabulary of teaching (yārāh = to instruct/teach, the root of tôrāh), quietness (ḥāraš = to be silent), and understanding (bîn = to discern) frames Job's request in precisely the terms of wisdom-instruction. He is not refusing wisdom; he is demanding that the friends actually deliver it.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'How compelling honest words are!' (mah-nîmrĕṣû millîm-yōšer = how forceful/painful are words of uprightness!) — the irony is that the friends' words are <em>not</em> honest: they are using the standard wisdom vocabulary (v27) while misapplying it to Job's situation. 'But what does your argumentation prove?' (ûmah-yôḵîaḥ hôḵēaḥ mikkkem = and what does reproof from you prove?) — the forensic question yôḵîaḥ / hôḵîaḥ (from yāḵaḥ = to reprove/argue) returns us to the legal metaphor. The friends' arguments are formally correct but prove nothing because they rest on a false premise (Job's guilt).</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Do you intend to reprove words, as if the speech of a despairing man were just wind?' — lĕhôḵîaḥ millîm taḥšĕḇû (do you think to reprove words alone?); ûlĕrûaḥ ʾimrê nōʾāš (and the words of a desperate man are wind?). The dismissal of suffering-language as 'mere words' or 'just wind' is the theological move Job is challenging: the friends are treating his complaints as formally invalid (wind = rûaḥ, meaningless breath) rather than as genuine testimony from someone in genuine distress. This mirrors the dismissal of lament in some religious communities: that mourning and protest are signs of inadequate faith.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'You would cast lots over an orphan and sell out your friend' — the accusation escalates: the friends' callous attitude toward Job's suffering is equivalent to the most extreme forms of exploitation (casting lots = gambling over a helpless person's fate; yattîlû ʿal-yāṯôm = you throw lots upon an orphan). The orphan (yātôm) is the paradigmatic figure of social vulnerability whose protection is the test of societal justice throughout the OT (Exod 22:22; Deut 10:18; Ps 68:5; Isa 1:17; James 1:27). The comparison says: the friends treat Job the way a heartless gambler treats an orphan.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Be willing to look me in the face' — the appeal for direct, honest engagement: p̄ĕnû-nāʾ ʾēlay wĕʿal-p̄ānêḵem ʾim-ʾăḵazzēḇ (turn to me; will I lie to your faces?). The face-to-face encounter is the mark of authentic relationship in the OT: YHWH speaks to Moses 'face to face, as a man speaks with his friend' (Exod 33:11); Jacob names Peniel 'the face of God' after surviving his encounter (Gen 32:30). The friends who won't look Job in the face are refusing the most basic form of human-divine encounter: honest presence.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Come back now; let there be no injustice here' — šûḇû-nāʾ ʾal-tĕhî ʿawlāh = return please; let there be no iniquity. šûḇ (to return/repent) is the standard word for both physical return and theological repentance; here Job uses it to call the friends back to him, back to honest engagement. 'My integrity is at stake' (wĕšûḇ ʾôḏ ṣiḏqî-ḇāh = and turn back again — my righteousness is in it); Job's ṣeḏeq (righteousness/integrity) is at stake in this encounter. The word ṣeḏeq used of Job himself will become one of the book's central contested terms.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Job closes his reply by asserting the reliability of his own moral sense: 'is there any wrongdoing on my tongue?' (hăyēš-bĕlišônî ʿawlāh = is there iniquity on my tongue?) and 'can my own sense of taste not tell what is harmful?' (ʾim-ḥiḵḵî lōʾ-yāḇîn hawwôṯ = does not my palate perceive disasters?). The palate-as-discernment metaphor (12:11; 33:2; 34:3 for ear/palate testing words) closes the chapter: Job has the same capacity for moral discernment that the friends have, and he asserts it is working correctly. His complaint is not the raving of an impaired moral sensor but the accurate report of a properly functioning one.</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 7 continues Job's address, shifting from the friends to a direct address of God beginning at v7. The chapter opens with one of Job's most powerful existential statements: 'does not man have <em>ṣāḇāʾ</em> on earth?' — ṣāḇāʾ means <em>hard military service/forced labor</em> (Num 4:3; 31:14; 2 Chr 17:18). The same term is used in Isaiah 40:2 ('her hard service [ṣāḇāʾ] is completed') for Babylon's completion of exile. This word choice frames human existence not as peaceful creature-life but as a tour of duty — exhausting, obligatory, under command — with a fixed term and a promised relief. The hireling (śāḵîr) simile of v2 develops the labor metaphor.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The hired worker (śāḵîr) is a specific social category in ancient Israel: the day-laborer who depends on daily wages for survival (Lev 19:13 'do not hold back the wages of a hired worker overnight'; Deut 24:14-15 on same-day payment requirements; Jas 5:4 condemning withholding wages). The śāḵîr longing for the shade (ṣēl) and watching for wages (yiqweh p̄ŏʿullāṯô) describes the specific experience of agricultural day-labor: the sun is the enemy, shade is rest, and wages are the only point of endurance. Job's life feels like this work — sustained only by the possibility of eventual payment/relief.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Months of futility' (yārĕḥê-šāwʾ = months of emptiness/vanity) — šāwʾ (emptiness/nothingness/vanity) is the same word used in the third commandment and in Job 31:5; its application to entire months gives Job's suffering a temporal expanse. 'Wearisome nights assigned to me' (lēlôṯ ʿāmāl sippĕr-lî = nights of trouble are counted out for me) — sāpar in the nip'al = to be assigned/meted out; the nights are not random but assigned by divine decree, making the exhaustion purposive rather than accidental.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The insomnia complaint (šāḵabû wāʾōmar = I lie down and say; mātay ʾāqûm = when will I rise?) reflects the ancient understanding that night brought either rest or terror. The Psalms frequently reference nighttime terror and insomnia as part of divine abandonment: Ps 6:6 ('all night I flood my bed with weeping'); Ps 22:2 ('by night I cry out and am not silent'); 30:5 ('weeping may stay for the night, but rejoicing comes in the morning' — the positive version). Job's nights extend toward dawn (wĕnešep̄ = twilight/dawn) with tossing (nidûḏ = restlessness) rather than resolution.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The physical description of Job's skin disease: 'covered with worms and clods of earth' (rimmāh wĕgeṯ-ʿāpār = worms and clods of dust) and 'skin cracks and oozes' (ʿôrî rāgaʿ wayyimmāʾēs = my skin hardens and flows again). The description fits severe dermatitis or the later-identified condition of Job as involving boils (2:7), which in ancient medicine could indeed lead to secondary infection with larvae. The medical precision is notable; the description serves both to document the physical reality and to establish that Job's complaints are grounded in observable bodily suffering, not emotional exaggeration.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'My days are swifter than a weaver's shuttle' (yāmay qallû miṇ-ʾōreḡ = my days are faster than a shuttle) — the shuttle (ʾōreḡ) that passes back and forth across the loom at great speed is a metaphor for the brevity of human life found also in Isa 38:12 (Hezekiah's lament: 'like a weaver I have rolled up my life, and he has cut me from the loom'). 'Without hope' (wĕyiḵlû ḇĕʾēn tiqwāh = they end without hope) — tiqwāh (hope) appears here at the very end of the verse, its absence the defining quality of the days' passing. The shuttle goes fast and arrives nowhere.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Remember that my life is but a breath' — Job's direct address to God begins: zĕḵōr kî-rûaḥ ḥayyāy (remember that a breath is my life). The imperative zĕḵōr (remember!) directed at God is a characteristic move in Hebrew lament: Ps 25:7; 74:2; 89:47,50; Lam 3:19 all use it to call God to action on the basis of covenant memory. The breath-of-life (rûaḥ ḥayyāy) echoes Gen 2:7 where God breathed the breath of life (nišmaṯ ḥayyîm) into the creature; Job's breath is the same divine breath now running short. 'My eyes will never again see happiness' (lōʾ-tāšûḇ ʿênî lirʾôṯ ṭôḇ = my eyes will not return to see good) — the return-to-happiness (šûḇ + ṭôḇ) is the standard formula for restoration; Job denies its applicability.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'The eye of whoever sees me will see me no more' — the verse describes the irreversibility of death from the perspective of social relationships: the one who currently sees Job (rōʾēnî) will look for him (tĕšûrēnî = you will look carefully) but find him gone. The social-death aspect of Job's dying is its disappearance from the web of relationships. 'You will look for me but I will be gone' echoes the wisdom tradition's statements about the disappearance of the wicked (Ps 37:36; 10 'I looked but he was gone') — but Job applies this dissolution vocabulary to himself, one of the righteous.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'As a cloud vanishes and is gone, so the one who descends to Sheol does not come up' — three images of irreversibility: the vanishing cloud (ʿānān kālāh wĕyēleḵ = a cloud consumes itself and goes), the descent to Sheol (šĕʾôl yōrēḏ = the one going down to Sheol), and the non-ascent (lō-yaʿăleh = does not come up). Sheol in the OT is generally the undifferentiated realm of the dead — not hell but the shadowy underworld where the dead dwell as rĕp̄āʾîm (shades). The one-way downward direction dominates: Job's point is that death reversal is impossible, setting up his resurrection question in 14:14.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'He will never return home, and his place will know him no more' — the dead man's 'place' (mĕqômô = his position in the household and community) no longer recognizes him; the familiar social slot is vacated permanently. The vocabulary of place-knowing/not-knowing (wĕlō-yakkîrennû ʿôḏ mĕqômô = his place will no longer recognize him) echoes the legal reality of social identity: a person's place in the community is their standing, property rights, and family relationships — all of which evaporate at death. Ps 103:16 uses the same image: 'his place will know him no more.'</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Therefore I will not hold back' — lāḵēn gam-ʾănî lōʾ ʾaḥśōḵ (therefore even I will not restrain myself). The logical transition: the irreversibility of death + the current suffering = the necessity of speaking now. 'I will speak in the anguish of my spirit and complain in the bitterness of my soul' — ʾăḏabbĕrāh bĕṣar rûḥî ʾāśîaḥ bĕmar nap̄šî. The vocabulary of anguish (ṣar rûaḥ = distress of spirit) and bitterness (mar nepeš = bitter soul; used in 1 Sam 1:10 of Hannah; Ruth 1:20 of Naomi at her lowest) places Job in the company of those whose extreme suffering authorized extreme expression before God.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Am I the sea, or a sea monster, that you place a guard over me?' — hayam-ʾănî ʾim-tannîn kî-ṯāśem ʿālay mišmār. This verse directly invokes <em>Canaanite creation mythology</em>. In the Ugaritic Baal Cycle, Yam (the sea) is the chaotic, hostile deity whom Baal must defeat to establish order; in Babylonian mythology, Tiamat is the sea-chaos monster whom Marduk battles. YHWH's 'guard' over the sea connects to Gen 1:9-10 (God gathering the waters within their bounds) and Jer 5:22 ('I placed sand as the boundary for the sea'). Job's ironic self-comparison to Yam/tannîn (sea monster) asks: am I a cosmic threat to be contained? Why does God guard me so closely if I am just a man?</p>",
    "13": "<p>The irony of the bed: 'when I say, my bed will comfort me, my couch will ease my complaint' — wĕʾāmartî tĕnaḥămēnî ʿarśî yiśśāʾ bĕśiḥî miškāḇî (my couch will lift up my complaint). The bed is the natural place of comfort and sleep in the ancient world; Ps 4:4 ('commune with your own heart on your bed and be silent') and Ps 63:6 ('I remember you on my bed') present the bed as a place of communion with God. Job has lost even this: the bed that should comfort terrifies (v14).</p>",
    "14": "<p>'You terrify me with dreams and frighten me with visions' — wĕḥittaṯannî baḥălōmôṯ ûmēḥezyōnôṯ tĕḇahălannî. Dreams and visions in the ancient world were the primary channel of divine communication (Gen 28:12 Jacob's dream; 1 Kgs 3:5 Solomon's dream; Dan 7 Daniel's visions). The expectation was that dreams brought divine messages; for the dreams to bring terror rather than guidance is another form of divine perversion of normal covenant channels. Eliphaz received a terrifying nocturnal vision as the basis for his opening argument (4:12-17) — Job now reports the same phenomenon as pure torment rather than revelation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'So that I would choose strangulation and death rather than this suffering in my body' — wayyiḇḥar maḥănaq nap̄šî māwet mēʿaṣmôṯāy = my soul chooses strangulation, death, rather than my bones. The preference for strangulation over continued existence is the most extreme expression of Job's death-wish in the book; it goes beyond the rhetorical 'let me die' of ch6 to specifying the means of death preferred. Strangulation (maḥănaq, from ḥānaq = to strangle; Nahum 2:12 uses it for the lion strangling prey) was not a normal mode of death but represented a swift, complete end. In context it reveals the depths of Job's physical and psychological suffering.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'I am through with it; I would not live forever' — māʾastî lōʾ-lĕʿōlām ʾeḥyeh (I have rejected it; I will not live forever). The renunciation of eternal life as a good would be theologically scandalous in most OT contexts — long life is among God's greatest blessings (Ps 91:16; Prov 3:16). Job's rejection of it expresses that the quality of existence has made its continuation undesirable. 'Leave me be, for my days are only a breath' — ḥaḏal mimmennî kî-heḇel yāmāy = leave off from me for my days are vapor/breath. The ḥeḇel (vapor/breath/vanity) of Ecclesiastes' world-view appears here as Job's self-assessment: his life is the emptiness Qohelet analyzes.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'What is man, that you should make so much of him?' — mah-ʾĕnôš kî tĕgaḏlĕlennû = what is a mortal that you would magnify him? This is a deliberate <em>inversion</em> of Psalm 8:4 ('what is man that you are mindful of him, and the son of man that you care for him?'). In Psalm 8, the question is asked in wonder and gratitude: human beings are surprisingly honored given their cosmic insignificance. Job inverts the emotional valence: the same divine attention that Psalm 8 celebrates as gracious, Job experiences as oppressive over-surveillance. The NT trajectory: Heb 2:6-8 quotes Ps 8:4-6 and applies it to Christ as the one in whom human dignity is fully realized; the gap between Job's experience of divine over-attention and Psalm 8's praise of it is bridged only in the incarnation.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Testing him every morning, examining him every moment' — wattip̄qĕḏennû liḇqārîm = you visit/examine him every morning; lirgāʿîm tiḇḥānenû = every moment you test him. The double-temporal structure (morning + moment) describes total temporal surveillance. In the OT, divine examination in the morning is associated with both blessing (Ps 5:3 'in the morning I lay my requests before you'; Lam 3:23 'his mercies are new every morning') and judgment (Exod 7:15 'go to Pharaoh in the morning'). For Job, the morning visit that should bring mercies brings only renewed scrutiny and pain.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'How long will you not look away from me?' — mah-tišʿeh mimmenî = how long will you look away from me? The syntax is ambiguous: does Job want divine attention or want it to stop? Compare 7:7 ('remember me') with v19 ('stop looking at me'). The tension captures the paradox of God-experience in suffering: the God who is present but only as surveillance is worse than absence, yet absence would mean abandonment. 'Long enough to swallow' (ʿaḏ-bilʿî rōqî = until I swallow my saliva) — the extreme body-language of momentary relief: even a second's break to swallow would be something.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'If I have sinned, what have I done to you, O watcher of mankind?' — ḥāṭāʾṯî mah-ʾep̄ʿal lāḵ nōṣēr hāʾāḏām (what have I done to you, watcher/guardian of humanity?). The divine epithet nōṣēr hāʾāḏām (guardian of mankind) is two-edged: a guardian normally protects, but this guardian is experienced as oppressive. 'Why have you made me your target?' (lāmmāh śamtannî lĕmip̄gāʿ lāḵ = why have you set me as a target for yourself?) — mip̄gāʿ is the target for an arrow (from pāgaʿ = to strike/meet; in military contexts the point of attack). Job as God's archery target connects back to 6:4's arrows of Shaddai — the consistent military metaphor frames Job's suffering as God conducting warfare against his servant.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Why do you not pardon my offense and forgive my sin?' — wĕlāmmāh lōʾ-tiśśāʾ pišʿî = why do you not lift up/carry my transgression? nāśāʾ ʿāwōn (to carry away iniquity) is the standard OT vocabulary for divine forgiveness: the same phrase appears in Exod 34:7 (YHWH 'carrying iniquity, transgression, and sin'), Ps 32:5, and Mic 7:18 ('who is a God like you, who pardons sin and forgives transgression?'). Job's final verse uses precisely this forgiveness vocabulary — not as a confession of guilt but as a question: why not use your own stated capacity for forgiveness now, before I die? 'For soon I shall lie down in the dust' — the urgency of mortality: forgiveness deferred past death is forgiveness that cannot be received.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'job')
    merge_comm(c, JOB57)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'job', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in JOB57.values())
    print(f'job mkt-context: wrote {count} verses for ch 5–7')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
